name: dipeptidase E
reaction: Dipeptidase E catalyses the hydrolysis of dipeptides Asp!Xaa. It does not act on peptides with N-terminal Glu, Asn or Gln, nor does it cleave isoaspartyl peptides
comment: A free carboxy group is not absolutely required in the substrate since Asp-Phe-NH2 and Asp-Phe-OMe are hydrolysed somewhat more slowly than dipeptides with free C-termini. No peptide larger than a C-blocked dipeptide is known to be a substrate. Asp-NH-Np is hydrolysed and is a convenient substrate for routine assay. The enzyme is most active near pH 7.0, and is not inhibited by di-isopropylfluorophosphate or phenylmethanesulfonyl fluoride. Belongs in peptidase family S51.

references.title: The structure of aspartyl dipeptidase reveals a unique fold with a Ser-His-Glu catalytic triad.
references.journal: Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. U. S. A. 97 (2000) 14097-102.

references.title: Peptidase E, a peptidase specific for N-terminal aspartic dipeptides, is a serine hydrolase.
